UFC Strike Moments are digital collectibles that launched January 2022; they are highlights of some of the most Iconic Moments in the Octagon

Unfortunately it’s in the state of a rebuild (UFC Strike just migrated from the Flow Blockchain to the Aptos Blockchain) so it will be a little while until it’s properly back in action

The UFC Strike Website and Marketplace are still being rebuilt; There should be news on that soon though. There’s a new Series launching for UFC Strike when it’s officially rebooted, Series 3; Series 0, 1 and 2 are retired (although there are remaining Series 2 Moments for rewards during Series 3)

Generally the best way to get started will be Pack Drops; although no specific details of Series 3 have been revealed yet

The most exciting aspect of UFC Strike has by far been its growing ties to the UFC which have allowed unprecedented access and IRL rewards; Fight.iD and the Concept Labs team really know how to make an outstanding Loyalty Rewards program that is top of its class imo

I’ll try to give folks a better introduction into UFC Strike Moments. Considering there are 7 Tiers it seems proper to introduce 1 Tier each day and discuss some of the finer points of each Tier

I’ll start out with Common Moments:
First introduced in the earliest days of UFC Strike, Series 0 Common Moments were minted to 23,490
*Ilia Topuria defeats world-renowned Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu specialist Ryan Hall with a barrage of dominant right hands while skillfully avoiding submission.*
*Paddy "The Baddy" Pimblett earns a TKO victory landing a series of punches against Luigi Vendramini, in his UFC debut.*

*Khamzat "Borz" Chimaev caps off a near perfect performance against Li Jingliang at UFC 267. Chimaev submitted Jingliang via a rear naked choke without absorbing a single strike during the entire fight.*

Series 0 only lasted 1 Month and consisted of 25 Common Moments and 10 Champion Moments. Series 0 Common Tier Sets were the easiest to Collect; although post migration it might be trickier
(Also imo FP will most likely be claimed from a lot of Series 0-2’s Moments)

The Commons were minted FAR higher than any future UFC Strike Moments, and are much closer to 16,000 Mints at this point

Next up was Series 1, introduced in March 2022

Common Mints were reduced to 12,000 maximum; although most Series 1 Commons are closer to 3,000-4,000 at this point
*Khabib "The Eagle" Nurmagomedov finishes Thiago Tavares in the first round with a clean left uppercut and massive elbows on the ground for his third straight UFC victory.*
*Jack Della Maddalena secures an epic TKO victory after catching Pete Rodriguez with a thunderous left hand in the first round of his UFC debut.*
Trying not to fill up the whole discord 😅, sorry! I wish there was an easier way to show the history of it all, but it’s the best way I can think of

Next up was Series 2; which launched November 2023

UFC Strike redesigned its Moments entirely from that point forward, with much more dynamic Moments and a bigger (imo) better experience 

There was also a significant focus on scarcity from the get-go starting in Series 2. Common Moments were minted to a Max of 3,000. 

Imo Series 2 Common Tier Sets would be the hardest to complete, as it’s roughly the size of Series 1; but far harder to track down Moments already

*In his first-ever UFC appearance, Alex "Poatan" Pereira showed what all the hype was about with this vicious jumping knee KO against Andreas Michailidis. Early in the second round, Pereira jumps into a switch knee that lands flush to the face of Michailidis, finishing the fight via KO.*

*Before establishing his legacy as the best light heavyweight of all time, Jon "Bones" Jones dominated Vladimir Matyushenko from the crucifix position, raining down elbows until the TKO stoppage in round 1.*

That’s a fairly good introduction into what Common Moments are. ngl I was trying to avoid it turning into an information dump, but it felt important to elaborate *Why* Common Moments range so much in Mint, and what led to that

It depends a lot on how significant the fight was etc, there are (a few) Moments even in the higher tiers that ended in a Decision. Usually those are designated as Striking or Grappling Moments

The most significant Moments like that which immediately spring to mind are Alex Volkanovski’s Champion when he beat Ortega after surviving the mounted guillotine, or Max Holloways Champion where he outboxed Ortega

UFC Strike Moments are minted by UFC Strike itself; the vast majority are Minted into Pack Drops, although there are  a few exceptions

Primarily Challenges, which are bi-monthly events that are usually based around UFC Events (especially UFC PPV Premium Events).
Those are often Collection based; although the hardest challenges required Collector’s to Burn specific Moments to earn that Challenges reward Moment

Here is an example of an earlier Challenge; they range in difficulty a great deal depending on what the reward Moment is. For Challenges that earn Common or Uncommon Moments they are fairly easy to accomplish; but from Rare on up they get a lot trickier. Usually Challenges for an Epic or (a very rare) Champion Challenge fall on UFC PPVs and are the most difficult to Complete

Been really busy today, got enough time to breakdown Uncommon Moments though

Fortunately UFC Strike Moment/Tier breakdowns become a lot more streamlined  after Common Tier; Common Tier had the most balancing and a lot more to explain

Uncommon UFC Strike Moments were introduced in Series 2 and are minted between 1,000-2,499 Moments 

It’s a much more accessible Tier than Rare (although funnily enough the Rare Tier started in Series 1 with 1,500 Max Mint; the relative standard for Uncommons)

*Kicking off a rivalry that would go on to define the legacy of Dustin Poirier, "The Notorious" Conor McGregor made quick work of "The Diamond" at featherweight, landing a left-hand flush to the temple and finishing with several follow-up shots in round 1.*

*Reinier "RdR" de Ridder took on Gerald Meerschaert at UFC Fight Night: Magny vs Prates in his UFC debut. After a series of high-level scrambles, de Ridder secured an arm-triangle submission early in the third round, earning the 14th submission victory of his professional MMA career.*

*Landing one of the rarest submissions ever seen in MMA, Charles "do Bronx" Oliveira showed off his world-class jiu-jitsu early in his UFC career against Eric Wisely. While passing guard, Oliveira sits back into a traditional ashi garami position, and as Wisely rolls to escape, Oliveira transitions into a calf slicer, pulling his way up to Wisely's back and finishing the submission.*

I should emphasize that UFC Strike has been outstanding about keeping Fighters Moments scarce, each fighter has only been allowed 1 Moment per Tier at most (technically that Tiering limit is per Series, but no fighters have had any repeat Tier Moments)

Even Conor McGregor only has 3 Moments total so far across the platform after nearly 4 Years (this Uncommon, his (UFC Debut) Rare Moment, and his Champion Moment of his Historic win over Jose Aldo)

The 3rd Tier in UFC Strike is Rare Moments (Fandom are trickier to place, but much more scarce as a Retired Tier)

*"The Notorious" Conor McGregor KOs Marcus Brimage with a barrage of powerful punches in his **UFC Debut**.*

Series 1 Rares were minted from 250-2,500; but that was rebalanced in Series 2. Now Rare Moments are minted from 500-999

we need to connect our UFC Strike account to FightID yet?
It’ll will definitely be worth getting it connected in the near future; as it will connect Seamlessly with different aspects of the Fight.iD Ecosystem

Short term connecting both accounts allows folks to Claim FP; although that’s definitely mostly geared to folks who have Unclaimed UFC Strike Moments. Moments can only be claimed for FP once ever (1 Time per each individual Moment). After a specific UFC Strike Moment has been claimed it’s no longer possible for anyone to Claim FP off that Moment. 

So the primary way to Earn points from UFC Strike Boosts will be “New” UFC Strike Moments. Due to the Migration hiccups it’s difficult to build a Collection right now, and newly minted Series 3 Moments will be the only guaranteed way to claim FP points

I think the best option when Collecting UFC Strike Moments with a focus on boosting your FP Points will come with Series 3

There’s no great way to know if a Moment has been claimed for FP so far; so it would be pretty much hit or miss for Series 0, Series 1 and Series 2 Moments. Newly Minted Moments will always have FP to claim; but it’s too difficult to tell if a previously owned Moment has been claimed (right now)

Only 3 more UFC Strike Tiers to Introduce and here is where we start focusing on the most Hardcore Collectors

Epic Tier was introduced with Series 2 in November 2023; and quickly became a favorite of Collectors who were looking to add a more exclusive Set to their Collections

Minted from 100-499, these are some of the most sought after Moments in UFC Strike from the get-go; and typically are crucial parts of the Most Difficult Challenges

*Quinton "Rampage" Jackson delivered one of the most iconic knockouts in MMA history at Pride Critical Countdown 2004 against Ricardo Arona. Trapped in a triangle choke after absorbing several punishing upkicks, Jackson showcased his raw power with a thunderous slam that instantly rendered Arona unconscious.*

*Khabib "The Eagle" Nurmagomedov put his dominant grappling on full display against Michael Johnson at UFC 205. After imposing relentless pressure, Nurmagomedov secured a takedown in the first round and methodically wore Johnson down before locking in a tight kimura in the third, forcing the tap and extending his undefeated record.*

*After losing the light heavyweight title and tasting his first defeat in the Octagon in his last appearance, Jiri Prochazka aimed to get back on track for UFC gold in his matchup against Aleksander Rakic at UFC 300. After enduring several heavy leg kicks in the first round, Prochazka landed a vicious right hand midway through the second, following it up with an onslaught of strikes and relentless pressure to earn the TKO victory.*

*One of the most entertaining athletes to ever grace the Octagon, Dustin "The Diamond" Poirier rendered a historic performance on UFC's Fight Island at UFC 257 against "The Notorious" Conor McGregor. After stunning the Irishman with a big left hand, Poirier unleashed a flurry of punches, landing a finishing right hook, becoming the first person to finish McGregor by knockout.*

*Rematching perrenial contender Dustin Poirier after getting finished in their first fight, Justin "The Highlight" Gaethje avenged his loss in emphatic fashion, landing a knockout headkick in the second round, capturing the UFC BMF title in the process.*

*UFC Hall of Famer and former welterweight champion, "Ruthless" Robbie Lawler, prepared to make his final appearance in the Octagon at UFC 290 against fellow welterweight contender, Niko "The Hybrid" Price. Just half a minute into the first round, Lawler secured a clinch and landed a massive uppercut, delivering an epic KO to end his career in storied fashion.*

Epic Tier is one of the hardest Sets to obtain in UFC Strike, and the highest Set I personally own. Only the most dedicated Collectors have the Full Set, and most won’t part with any parts easily. Tbh I don’t think Series 2 Epic Sets will be possible to come by; and it would be far easier to aim for Series 3’s Epic Tier

Trying to keep my opinions and color commentary minimal when I’m explaining Tiers, but also share any insights from being a very dedicated Collector. I don’t think it would be easy to obtain a Full Series 2 Epic Tier Set because a few of those Moments are close to the Tiers Low Mint Cap (100) and some Moments only have had 5-10 Listing ever.

Even when there is a structured Marketplace some Series 2 Epic Moments are extremely hard to come by
